{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:05:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:05:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1902"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1902"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.9,0.02,0.06,0.01,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84685"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1902"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68972"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2770"},{"type":"tags","id":"2840"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4993"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5262"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5534"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84685"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 63-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with swelling and stiffness in the joints of her hands and wrists. These symptoms are worse in the morning, lasting around one hour, and improve with activity throughout the day. The symptoms began when she was 35 years old but have recently worsened to the point where she has difficulty opening her front door.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe has no significant medical history apart from a fractured radius in her teenage years. She does not take any regular medications. She is a current smoker with a 40 pack-year history and drinks two to three standard drinks of alcohol per night. She is a retired typist. She has a family history of psoriasis in her aunt.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 30 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Examination of her hands reveals the following appearance (image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid arthritis","Osteoarthritis","Psoriatic arthropathy","Gout","Ulnar nerve injury"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of \u003Cstrong\u003Erheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E, including morning stiffness lasting over 30 minutes, symmetrical joint involvement, and characteristic hand deformities. The patient also has several risk factors including female gender, smoking history, and age of onset in the fourth decade.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsteoarthritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes non-inflammatory joint pain that worsens with use and improves with rest. Morning stiffness in osteoarthritis usually lasts less than 30 minutes. It predominantly affects the distal interphalangeal joints rather than the metacarpophalangeal joints seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPsoriatic arthropathy\u003C/strong\u003E typically develops after skin manifestations of psoriasis. While there is a family history of psoriasis, the patient has no personal history of skin changes. The pattern of joint involvement is typically asymmetric, unlike the symmetric pattern seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGout\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents as acute episodes of monoarthritis, most commonly affecting the first metatarsophalangeal joint. While chronic tophaceous gout can affect multiple joints, the pattern of deformity and morning stiffness would be unusual.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUlnar nerve injury\u003C/strong\u003E can cause clawing of the fourth and fifth digits but would not explain the symmetric polyarthritis, morning stiffness, or metacarpophalangeal joint changes seen in this patient. Neurological symptoms and signs would be expected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Morning stiffness lasting over 30 minutes is characteristic of inflammatory arthritis like rheumatoid arthritis.","Classic hand deformities in rheumatoid arthritis include ulnar deviation, swan neck deformity, and MCP joint subluxation.","Female gender, smoking, and older age are key risk factors for rheumatoid arthritis."],"references":["Wasserman AM. Diagnosis and management of rheumatoid arthritis. Am Fam Physician. 2011 Dec 1;84(11):1245\u201352. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2011/1201/p1245.html","Neal SJ, Fields KB. Peripheral Nerve Entrapment and Injury in the Upper Extremity. AFP. 2010 Jan 15;81(2):147\u201355. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2010/0115/p147.html","Doughty CT, Bowley MP. Entrapment Neuropathies of the Upper Extremity. Med Clin North Am. 2019 Mar;103(2):357\u201370. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30704687/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1902"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16592"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16592","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16592"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e5cac3ab-9aa7-4129-8a2d-508a3bd80c96.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e5cac3ab-9a